.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomoftenacity>AtomOfTenacity </A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 109<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/27/03 9:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=921.topic>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/atom_of_tenacity.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Who is going to win the X-Prize?</span><hr size=1> I think that Scaled Composites is going to win the X-Prize hands down. Why? Because the other two major contenders - Starchaser Industries and Canadian Arrow - are relying on cumbersome rockets that have horrible turn around rates whereas Scaled will be a &quot;gas and go&quot; affair that has a better chance of not only winning the prize but securing future tickets from space tourists. <br>
If you had the choice of strapping yourself into a V-2 or Space Ship One, which would you chose? <br>
Even if Starchaser and Arrow are successful there is no way for them to be economically viable as Rutan will be able to fly much more often.<br>
And just think if XCOR can get their Xerus craft going – that would be even better than Rutan’s setup.<br>
But, I have always been skeptical of what these clowns are doing trying to make money off a V-2 rocket that’s been stretched 8ft. <br>
I mean come on now, I am going to go through all the careful preparation of launching a rocket and then after launching it go running around hither and yon recovering the pieces in grassy fields and meadows and then have all that turn around time associated with this system –it’s the stupid space shuttle all over again. <br>
Meanwhile, Rutan and XCOR will soaring in the skies, returning to earth to refuel and have flight after flight in rapid succession and thus will attract passengers better then a big vertical rocket would. Rockets have much more delays then planes with rockets in them.<br>
Besides, the prize expires in 2005 and Starchaser and Arrow still have a long ways to go, we better pray that they use dogs for the first few flights… <br>
    <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=lunarorbit>lunarorbit</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.thespacerace.com/canflag.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 36<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/28/03 7:43 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=921.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.cogeco.ca/~jonesk/manonmoon2.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Who is going to win the X-Prize?</span><hr size=1> I think a lot of the space tourists will be looking for an experience similar to the good old days where astronauts launched atop rockets in cramped little capsules. Rutan's method is basically just flying really high in an airplane... kind of boring.<br>
<br>
I think I would rather ride a rocket into space, it just seems more exciting to me.<br>
<br>
