 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=brp17>brp17</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 300<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/29/03 11:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=921.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Re Re: Who is going to win the X-Prize?</span><hr size=1> Only the protests that'd surely come about if any such idea was ever put into action. Can you imagine? Yikes. I personally think that the Canadian Arrow will win out, if not the X-prize then at least in the commercial applications, still I rather like the Space Ship One, it's an idea similar to one I've though of myself, and I rather like it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nukepulse>NukePulse</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 80<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/3/03 3:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=921.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Re Re: Who is going to win the X-Prize?</span><hr size=1> I like the Canadian approach myself. I also agree that there is a big difference between a slow boring climb to altitude (yawn)and being launched to the same altitude on board a blazing rocket.<br>
<br>
Hey I favor an Orion ground launch myself Dusty. I'll bring the beer you bring the welding goggles and iodine tablets. See you at Jackass flats!<br>
<br>
I think that launching an 8,000-ton Orion from the ground is the way to go as far as I am concerned. If we build it on the ground then we could make the thing out of high alloy steel like a warship strong, sturdy, redundant, reliable, reusable and radiation resistant. If it is built on and launched from the ground it will be useful for three to five decades. <br>
<br>
Think about it, if we build some sort of watered down mini Orion in orbit the transportation cost of putting the pieces in orbit will be the single largest cost. Remember what it cost to put the S-1 truss on the ISS. The S-1 truss cost $120,000,000.00 to build and another $500,000,000.00 to install the thing on the ISS.<br>
<br>
Another more serious cost of the 'built in orbit' concept is that the design will be tainted by the minimum weight criterion cost over run disease. It will also be a flimsy tin plated goose. That alone will make the mini Orion 5 to 7 times as expensive as the full sized ground launched version and far less capable.<br>
<br>
Another problem with constructing it in orbit is the fact that it takes a great deal of time and effort to get even simple jobs done in zero G.  Remember that the Hubbell telescope fix took many, many hours and all they really did was replace 2 suitcase sized black boxes and attach a pair of bifocals on the thing. In the end they couldn’t even close the equipment bay door on the telescope and had to rig it with a nylon strap. No, building it in orbit is not the solution. Ground launch is the solution.<br>
<br>
Viva La V-2!!<br>
Viva La Ground Launch!!<br>
<br>
NukePulse<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=spacedrive@nuclearspace>Spacedrive</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 93<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/3/03 8:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=921.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Who is going to win the X-Prize?</span><hr size=1> It looks like Rutan's group not only have all of the basic hardware built, they have also flight tested it to some extent. They have to be the odds-on favorite, but Canadian Arrow and Armadillo Aerospace should be able to get something flying pretty soon. There may even be another competitor that has a secret program ready to be unveiled that could pull the rug from under Burt, it's really great to watch the competitive spirit in full bore.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=archiebald>archiebald</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 23<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/3/03 9:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=921.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://wb.ctk23.ne.jp/~archie/i/arch_port.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Who is going to win the X-Prize?</span><hr size=1> Didn't I read somewhere that Rutan's group were assisted in part by funding from the military?<br>
